Kim Jong Il appreciates revolutionary opera "Sea of Blood" 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, October 19 (KCNA) - Leader Kim Jong Il appreciated a revolutionary opera "Sea of Blood" at the Mansudae Art Theatre yesterday on the occasion of the 30th anniversary of the Phibada Opera Troupe.
 He was accompanied by director of the general political department of the Korean People's Army Jo Myong Rok, minister of the People's Armed Forces Kim Il Chol, secretaries Jon Pyong Ho, Choe Thae Bok, Kim Kuk Thae, Jong Ha Chol and Kim Ki Nam and leading officials of the WPK Central Committee and others.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After seeing the opera he personally met the leading members and actors and actresses who worked heart and soul to carry through the literary and art policy of the party from the beginning of the revolution in opera. He had a cordial talk with them to learn about their work and life in detail and highly praised their meritorious services for  the development of Juche-based art. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He said the creators and artistes of the Phibada Opera Troupe instilled the truth of struggle into our people through more than 1,500 performances given before them in the past 30 years. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 "Sea of Blood," "The Flower Girl,"  "A True Daughter of The Party" and other revolutionary operas with ever-lasting vitality are a good textbook for class education, the textbook for educating the rising generation in a revolutionary way, he said, underscoring the need to intensify opera performances before more people and servicemen. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He put forth tasks that would serve as a guideline in art creation and performance. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He had a souvenir picture taken with the creators and artistes of the Phibada Opera Troupe.

Friendly gathering held on anniversary of DPRK red cross society 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 19 (KCNA) -- The central committee of the DPRK Red Cross Society hosted a friendly gathering yesterday on the occasion of its 55th anniversary.
 Present there were Jang Jae On, chairman of the central committee of the society, Choe Chang Sik, vice-minister of public health, and other officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Invited there were Thomas Liew, head of the visiting aid delegation of the international federation of red cross and red crescent societies, members of the delegation, members of a delegation of the East Asia regional office of the International Committee of the Red Cross, representatives and members of the UN and non-governmental organizations and diplomatic envoys of Sweden and Germany here. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Speeches were made at the gathering to be followed by a briefing about major activities of the DPRK red cross society. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants talked about red cross activities, deepening the friendly feelings.

Chinese folk fine art exhibition opens 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 19 (KCNA) -- A Chinese folk fine art exhibition opened.
 On display in the exhibition hall are over 100 pieces of work showing part of Chinese folk fine art developing under the leadership of the Communist Party of China. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 An opening ceremony was held at the Pyongyang International House of Culture yesterday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present there were Kim Jun Han, vice-minister of culture, other officials concerned and working people in the city. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Chinese ambassador to the dprk wang guozhang and members of the embassy were also present there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 An opening address was made to be followed by a speech. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the end of the ceremony its participants looked round fine art works.

U.S. urged to opt for its forces' pullback from S. Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 19 (KCNA) -- The withdrawal of the U.S. forces from South Korea is a prerequisite for national reunification because Korea was divided by their occupation of South Korea and they are still present there, says Minju Joson today in a signed article.
 It urges the united states to opt for an early withdrawal of its forces from South Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the U.S. forces had not occupied South Korea, Korea would not have been divided into the north and the south and the issue of reunification would not have cropped up. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Hard historical facts prove that the U.S. forces' occupation of South Korea was the root cause of the Korea's division. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the U.S. forces pull out of South Korea and stop obstructing Korea's reunification, the Korean nation is fully capable of achieving the country's reunification by its own efforts. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Those who love the country and the nation are turning out in a vigorous struggle to force the U.S. forces to pull out of South Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 There is neither ground nor pretext for the U.S. to keep its forces in South Korea.

Japan's dangerous move for overseas aggression assailed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 19 (KCNA) -- Rodong Sinmun today in a signed commentary denounces the chief executive of Japan for working hard to revise the constitution in a bid to legislate on the reorganization of the "Self-Defense Forces" (SDF) into an "army".
 His proposal to revise the constitution signifies one formal step toward the practical moves to replace the "peace constitution" by a war constitution and legalize the moves for aggression and war, the commentary says, and goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The three services of Japan's armed forces going in the guise of the SDF in order not to give the impression that they are an "army" have grown to be the world's leading armed forces of aggression. After the adoption of the law related to the "U.S.-Japan defence cooperation guideline" the SDF has regained the right to participate in war and the right of belligerency. Japan, a military power, is getting all the more arrogant. The only stumbling block lying in its way is the present constitution which bans the use of armed forces. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The proposal made by the chief executive of Japan is aimed to legally allow Japan to keep huge regular modern combat forces and use them as it wishes under the pretext of the "state security and interests " and demonstrate their might before the world.    It is now trying to display its "skill" with the surprise attacks on the U.S. and its retaliation operation as a momentum. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 But Japan's reckless moves for overseas aggression are little short of digging its own grave.
